// Explicit view: a type-alias name in a type position shows its backing; the alias DECLARATION fills
// its elided ⟨type⟩ slot with the `type` meta (`base : type : int`). An alias is NOT a definition-form
// so it shows by default; the enclosing proc IS a form → hidden by default, shown under --full.
// RUN: %build/arche-analyzer --dump %s | grep -qxF "SYN 12 8 1 1 type type"
// RUN: %build/arche-analyzer --dump %s | grep -qxF "SYN 13 8 1 1 type type"
// RUN: %build/arche-analyzer --dump %s | grep -qxF "SYN 15 11 1 0 alias (i32)"
// RUN: %build/arche-analyzer --dump %s | grep -qxF "SYN 16 12 1 0 alias (i32)"
// Four SYN by default: 2 alias-decl `type` hints + 2 backing hints (the proc is hidden):
// RUN: test $(%build/arche-analyzer --dump %s 2>/dev/null | grep -c "^SYN ") -eq 4
// --full opts out, so the proc decl shows its form type too:
// RUN: %build/arche-analyzer --dump --full %s | grep -qxF "SYN 14 8 1 1 type proc()()"
base  :: int
level :: base
main  :: proc() {
  a : base  = 10;
  b : level = 20;
}
